## Learned User Preferences

- Cross-package shared markers/sentinels (e.g. tool-result offloading marker) live in `libs/chat` for shared use, never duplicated per-package.
- CAD agent system prompts must explicitly state production-grade, hyper-realistic design expectations and the target audience (architects/engineers) — without that domain context the LLM defaults to "toy" outputs because the simplest path looks acceptable; never rely on assumed business context.
- Tool-result offloading repeated-lookup substitution stays invisible to the user — render substituted `ToolMessage.content` as plain text indistinguishable from a fresh lookup.
- Prefer extending an existing RPC method (e.g. `readFile`) over adding a new one when the new behaviour is a near-superset — agent-surface complexity scales with method count.
- Prefer algorithmic, code-level solutions over bundler config or Vite plugins; middleware and transforms must be provider-agnostic (no model/provider-specific branching) — handle all providers generically; text normalization/sanitization AND malformed-payload healing (e.g. interrupted-stream tool inputs that fail strict schema validation) belong at the API layer (middleware/transforms/preprocess), never in UI components — the UI already renders fine without healing and per-render coercion misses every part already persisted in the DB; optimize for 3rd-party consumer DX; CAD export should not hardcode a single interchange format (e.g. GLB-only) or embed `@taucad/converter` as an internal runtime dependency — treat converters and third-party exporters (e.g. API-based format transformers) as injectable plugins with multiple providers allowed concurrently; agent-surface APIs (RPCs, tool inputs, system prompts) require explicit parameters with no silent `?? mainEntryFile`-style fallbacks so the LLM must commit to the file/target it intends; cross-cutting agent UI metadata (e.g. reasoning timing) namespaced under the generic `common` AI-SDK provider key — not a per-product `taucad` key — and typed end-to-end via `MyUIMessage` schemas (never `unknown` providerMetadata)

## Learned Workspace Facts

- `repos/claude-code` is the canonical reference for tool-call API simplicity and context-engineering patterns (offloading, RPC reuse) — consult before adding new tool-call API surface.
- Vertex Gemini implicit caching has async promotion lag — only the early prefix sticks (~85% hit, ~74K `cache_read` floor); explicit `cachedContent` Context Caching is needed for ~99% hit.
- Read-file line-number gutter prefixing belongs in the rendering layer, not the stored tool content — embedding line numbers in `tool-edit-tests.ts` storage breaks edit/replace pipelines.
- Tool input schemas for AI chat live in `libs/chat/src/schemas/tool-input.registry.ts` as a single registry keyed by tool name (`toolInputSchemas`/`getToolInputSchema`) and form the single source of truth for "is this input legal for this tool?"; used exclusively by the API-side preprocess in `libs/chat/src/schemas/message.schema.ts` to detect persisted `output-error` tool parts whose `input` no longer satisfies the per-tool strict schema (typically because the LLM stream was interrupted before the input finished serialising) and demote the malformed value into `rawInput` so `convertToModelMessages` → `messageContentSanitizerMiddleware` can pair a synthetic `tool_result` with the dangling `tool_use` block; UI never coerces or heals tool inputs (deliberately kept server-side only — UI renders fine without it and would otherwise miss every part already persisted in IndexedDB/Postgres); the contract is documented in `docs/policy/interrupted-tool-call-contract.md` and tested end-to-end via `apps/api/app/api/chat/interrupted-tool-roundtrip.test.ts` (real provider calls across anthropic/gemini/gpt), `apps/api/app/testing/interrupted-tool-providers.integration.test.ts`, and `apps/api/app/api/chat/middleware/message-content-sanitizer.middleware.test.ts` — never relax the strict schema at the pipe; always normalize partial inputs through the registry preprocess instead. Model benchmark suite at `apps/api/app/benchmarks/` — runner, geometry grader, HTML report generator for evaluating AI model performance on CAD tasks; uses OpenSCAD kernel for geometry validation; benchmark runner sends `kernel` metadata in chat messages which controls system prompt generation — must match target kernel; CLI at `apps/api/scripts/benchmark-models.mts` requires `node -r dotenv/config --import @oxc-node/core/register --import ./scripts/raw-loader.mts`; outputs JSON + HTML reports with geometry validation, GLB artifacts, and generated source code; `test.json` is per-file shape `{ [sourcePath]: { requirements: [] } }` so a project tests multiple geometry units concurrently — `targetFile` is required (no `?? mainEntryFile` fallback) on every agent-surface RPC and tool input (`fetch_geometry`, `capture_screenshot`, `test_model`, `edit_tests`, `get_kernel_result`); per-geometry-unit geometry artifacts use `${toolCallId}__${slug(targetFile)}.glb`; `rpcClientErrorCode` in `libs/chat/src/schemas/rpc.schema.ts` is the single catalog for RPC wire client error codes (UI imports it from `@taucad/chat`; do not recreate parallel UI error-code maps); reasoning timing is stateless server-side via `providerMetadata.common.reasoningStartedAtMs` on each `reasoning-start` part keyed by reasoning-block `id` (correlates interleaved thinking blocks across one message), surfaced via `MyUIMessage` typed schema — UI renders 'Thought briefly' (<1s) or 'Thought for Xs' from start/end timestamp diff (no client stopwatch, no clock-skew compensation); `agent-safeguards.middleware.ts` (`apps/api/app/api/chat/middleware/`) detects repeated identical tool failures (3 **sequential** errors on the same tool+input across consecutive turns) and injects a one-shot guidance message into the latest tool result steering the LLM to alternative actions — appended to the existing tool result so it does not invalidate Anthropic prompt cache; parallel/fan-out tool calls within a single assistant turn must NEVER trip the safeguard even when the same tool name appears multiple times (e.g. `create_file` invoked four ways in one fan-out is one parallel intent, not four sequential failed retries) — keying on tool+input alone is insufficient, the detector must require sequential turns AND distinct error events to avoid the false-positive that pushes the LLM to abandon legitimate parallel workloads; full system-prompt audit at `docs/research/system-prompt-audit.md` follows the gap-analysis checklist style of `filesystem-gap-analysis.md`; system prompts and tool-call descriptions use "geometry unit" everywhere — the "geometry unit" acronym is reserved for internal code only; kernel-specific test-failure recovery guidance lives inside each kernel's section of the system prompt (never as unconditional generic text that would mislead when paired with another kernel — e.g. don't reference OpenSCAD entry-point conventions in the Replicad section); each kernel ships a canonical multi-file example under `apps/api/app/api/chat/prompts/kernel-prompt-configs/<kernel>.prompt.example-multifile/` (jscad/manifold/opencascadejs/openscad/replicad/zoo) that the system prompt embeds verbatim to demonstrate idiomatic module decomposition; OpenSCAD multi-file examples MUST use `use <lib/file.scad>` (imports modules/functions only, no top-level execution) — `include <lib/file.scad>` inlines the entire file including any geometry calls at module scope, producing a duplicate copy of imported objects in the output (smoking-gun "robot rendered twice" symptom in early OpenSCAD examples); `test_model` dynamically creates the geometry unit on demand rather than asking the LLM to bootstrap — missing-file errors stay legitimate failures, not pre-bootstrapping requests; testing-related prompts push the LLM to add a top-level kernel-specific export so a file becomes testable rather than to skip writing the test; cross-provider thinking-block portability — Anthropic's `{type:"thinking", thinking, signature}` blocks are persisted verbatim by LangGraph's `PostgresSaver`, then crash on the next turn when the user switches to Gemini/Vertex because `@langchain/google-common`'s `messageContentComplexToPart` only handles `text|image_url|media|reasoning|input_audio` — fix by setting `outputVersion: "v1"` on `ChatAnthropic` (and `ChatVertexAI` once the fork picks up the upstream Gemini PRs) so `convertToV1FromAnthropicMessage` normalizes outgoing AIMessages to standard `{type:"reasoning", reasoning, signature}` blocks (`langchain-anthropic`'s `_formatStandardContent` re-emits as `thinking + signature` only when