tly one tool per assistant message" workaround is rejected (kills parallelism, breaks the prompt-cache prefix, fights every other Tau system-prompt section) — full design captured in `docs/research/parallel-tool-call-incremental-persistence.md`. Parallel-tool output interleaving: LangGraph's superstep model batches every fan-out tool's `tool-output-available` at superstep end (every Δ≈0ms across the parallel group), so the UI flips all loading spinners to "complete" simultaneously even though each tool's RPC finished at a different time — the goal is Cursor-style per-tool emission where each `tool-output-available` fires as soon as its own RPC returns (the test contract is captured by `apps/api/app/testing/parallel-tool-call.integration.test.ts`, which asserts each write's RPC fires immediately on its own `tool-input-available` and outputs interleave per-tool); rejected approaches enumerated in `docs/research/parallel-tool-output-interleaving.md`: a `TAU_LANGGRAPH_TOOL_CONCURRENCY` knob (wrong axis — drop the env var entirely), enforced inter-tool gaps or RPC sequencing (we want parallel RPCs, not serialised ones), validating partial JSON until it parses (optional fields silently skipped when they hadn't streamed yet), and an `EagerDispatchCallbackHandler` that hardcodes which tools own RPCs (couples tool-domain knowledge into the dispatcher — the architecturally correct trigger is the tool's own logic firing on `tool-input-available` so no extra layer needs to know which tools have RPCs); the solution must work WITH LangChain (no tricks, no fighting the framework — reframe the eigenquestion when proposed options all overengineer the problem). Eager tool dispatch architecture (POC GO verdict, `apps/api/app/api/chat/eager-dispatch/` + `docs/research/eager-tool-dispatch-poc.md`): a `BaseCallbackHandler` attached to `createAgent({...})` invocation receives `handleLLMNewToken` with populated `tool_call_chunks` during streaming and a final `handleLLMEnd` carrying parsed `AIMessage.tool_calls[]`; trigger eager `tool.invoke()` from S2 (index advance in `tool_call_chunks` for non-last tools) + S3 (`handleLLMEnd` for the last tool); `wrapToolCall` middleware short-circuits subsequent native `ToolNode` execution to return the cached eager result; the LangGraph `'custom'` writer must be captured explicitly from `request.runtime` inside a `wrapModelCall` hook and threaded into the handler — `getWriter()` (`AsyncLocalStorage`-backed) does NOT propagate reliably into `BaseCallbackHandler.handleLLMNewToken`; test ordering uses stream-relative assertions (compare against `lastBlock1ChunkTime`) rather than wall-clock thresholds (`t < 250ms`) to eliminate flake. Resumable chat streams (`docs/research/resumable-chat-streams.md`): `chat-error-service-unavailable.tsx`'s "Retry" button currently calls `useChatActions().regenerate()` → AI SDK `chat.regenerate()`, which slices off the trailing assistant message and wipes every part the user just watched stream in (file edits, thinking, tool calls) — this is the smoking-gun "I lost all my work" UX bug; the per-message `Try again` hover-footer affordance must KEEP its regenerate semantics (deliberate "regenerate from scratch with a fresh model"); the network-error banner must instead be a continuation (R1) plus transparent transport-level auto-retry with a Codex-style `Reconnecting... N/M` indicator that only surfaces the banner after the auto-retry budget is exhausted (R2); page-reload-tolerant `Chat.resumeStream()` + AI-SDK `resumable-stream` + Redis is R3 (deferred). `export_geometry` chat tool gating: system prompt instructs the agent to invoke `export_geometry` only when the user explicitly asks to export (the agent was over-eagerly exporting after every render); use POSITIVE wording per `docs/policy/context-engineering-policy.md` ("invoke when explicitly asked") rather than negative "do not export unless".
